    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-31T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-31T11:00:00-05:00" n="624"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d624">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Moscow/95: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-31T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 31, 1943—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Delam 46. For Acting Secretary of State and Byington.<note n="56"
                        xml:id="d624fn56">Homer M. Byington, Assistant Chief, Division of Current
                        Information.</note> New arrangements were made tonight with British and
                    Soviets regarding publicity. Text of joint statement with annexes which are
                    declaration of four nations on general security, declaration on German
                    atrocities, declaration regarding Italy and declaration on Austria will be
                    released by State Department, British and Soviet Foreign Offices for publication
                    and broadcast at 8 p.m. Moscow time (1 p.m. Eastern War Time) November l.<note
                        n="57" xml:id="d624fn57">The texts of the joint communiqué (Conference
                        Document No. 42, <ref target="#pg_741">p. 741</ref>), and the four
                        declarations were released to the press on November 1 as planned, and were
                        subsequently printed in the Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                            >Bulletin</hi>, November 6, 1943, pp. 307–311.</note> Moscow
                    correspondents will not send texts but will start filing stories at 6 p.m.
                    Monday for publication at 1 p.m. Eastern War Time. Above documents except Four
                    Nations Declaration which Department already has will be wired tonight for
                    release as above.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
